result.execSummary:
The defendant Rebecca Ann Nunez-Santos was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Attempt Attempt Robbery (Use of Force), a class E felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.32(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Rebecca Ann Nunez-Santos in court with Attorney Stephen Andrew Sargent.  Stephanie Krueger appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Case in court for plea/sentencing.  Parties have reached an agreement.  Court found the State has satisfied victims' rights law. Plea negotiations set forth on the record and agreed upon by the parties. 

AS TO COUNT 1:
Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Defendant further advised that if not a US citizen, deportation is possible. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, Addendum, and Elements/Jury Instructions received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

Pursuant to plea negotiations and on the motion of the State, Court ordered COUNT 2 DISMISSED BUT READ IN for the purpose of sentencing.  

Court advised the defendant that as a convicted felon, she may never own or possess a firearm.  Court advised defendant that she may not vote until his civil rights have been restored.  Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by the State, Defense Counsel, and Defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1:
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 3 YEARS with 94 days credit; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1.5 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 1.5 YEARS. 

Court finds the defendant IS eligible fore the WI Substance Abuse program and NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration program. 

The Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for 4 YEARS. 

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION/EXTENDED SUPERVISION IF REVOKED: 
- 9 MONTHS condition time with Huber release privileges for any medical treatment, AODA, and work. 
- AODA assessment and cooperate with any recommended treatment. 
- Provide DNA sample. 
- Full-time work, school, or combination of both. 
- Complete 100 hours of community service at a non-profit organization.  
- No contact with Walgreens located at 4688 S 108th St, Milwaukee, WI and no contact with victims KKK and LLM. 
- Follow all rules of supervision and follow through with any other treatment deemed necessary by the department. 
- Pay all applicable fees of supervision. 
- Restitution set at zero. 

Court ordered the defendant to pay all court costs, fees, and surcharges (including DNA) by the end of supervision. Failure to pay shall result in a civil judgment. If revoked, Court ordered that all court costs, fees, and surcharges be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections in an amount or percentage the Department (DOC) determines to be reasonable and as a condition of extended supervision.  DOC shall collect those sums. Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means. 

20 day appeal rights given.
